[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":2025},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F09\u002F19\u002Fday-5-nodejs-modules\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F09\u002F19\u002Fday-5-nodejs-modules\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F09\u002F19\u002Fday-5-nodejs-modules\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F09\u002F19\u002Fday-5-nodejs-modules\u002F":2001,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F09\u002F19\u002Fday-5-nodejs-modules\u002F":2010},"\u002Fnodejs\u002F20230919\u002F1426601281\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1985,"date":1986,"description":26,"extension":1987,"lang":1988,"meta":1989,"navigation":161,"path":1990,"readingMinutes":1991,"seo":1992,"standalone":1993,"stem":1994,"tags":1995,"tldr":1998,"updated":1986,"url":1999,"__hash__":2000},"content\u002Fen\u002FNodejs\u002Fday-5-nodejs-modules.md","Day 5 - Node.js Modules","4163119785",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1977},"minimark",[11,19,24,27,31,34,45,48,51,57,60,66,74,77,80,328,335,456,623,629,644,650,653,657,660,674,784,942,945,953,1042,1054,1068,1148,1151,1161,1169,1218,1296,1299,1370,1373,1378,1382,1390,1393,1399,1440,1443,1449,1586,1675,1678,1767,1770,1825,1828,1833,1837,1847,1864,1867,1873,1876,1883,1891,1908,1928,1931,1956,1963,1966,1970,1973],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":17,"src":18},"Modules","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fnodejs\u002Fithelp-nodejs-2023\u002Fisray_notarray_Next_you_will_play_the_role_of_a_translation_ass_fb062618-486b-4ded-a801-7d1c643ed3a1.png",[20,21,23],"h2",{"id":22},"intro","Intro",[12,25,26],{},"In the previous post we got familiar with some built-in modules. This time we're going to look at something kind of special but also kind of not — Modules.",[20,28,30],{"id":29},"what-are-modules","What are Modules?",[12,32,33],{},"If you came over from frontend with some dev experience, you probably have a basic concept of Modules. If you're just starting out, you might not be that familiar with them — but no worries, I'm dedicating this post to explain what Modules are, since they're really common in real-world dev.",[12,35,36,37,44],{},"Node.js supports two kinds of Modules: CommonJS and ECMAScript Modules (",[38,39,43],"a",{"href":40,"rel":41},"https:\u002F\u002Fisraynotarray.com\u002Fjavascript\u002F20210424\u002F616364031\u002F",[42],"nofollow","ES Modules (article in Mandarin)",").",[12,46,47],{},"So what are CommonJS and ECMAScript? There's some history here — these are two completely different module systems and standards.",[12,49,50],{},"Here's the interesting part: why doesn't Node.js just support ECMAScript? Why also support CommonJS?",[12,52,53],{},[15,54],{"alt":55,"src":56},"Thinking dinosaur","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fnodejs\u002Fithelp-nodejs-2023\u002F1690957490774.png",[12,58,59],{},"The main reason is that early JavaScript didn't have any concept of modularity. Historically, JavaScript was designed as a scripting language for frontend web pages, so it didn't provide a native module system. This forced early developers to write tons of code in a single file, which seriously hurt readability and maintainability. So devs started thinking about how to modularize code. As a server-side runtime, Node.js basically can't allow this kind of mess, so it defined its own module system — CommonJS. So technically CommonJS is ECMAScript's ancestor.",[12,61,62],{},[15,63],{"alt":64,"src":65},"Image source: web","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fnodejs\u002Fithelp-nodejs-2023\u002F4f771b4e3f28ec17f4887cf0e51d02d6~tplv-dy-resize-origshort-autoq-75%20330.jpeg",[67,68,71],"callout",{"title":69,"type":70},"Note","note",[12,72,73],{},"The most common module systems in the industry today are CommonJS and ES Modules — also called modularity standards. There's also AMD (Asynchronous Module Definition), but personally I've never used AMD.",[12,75,76],{},"Let's talk about what modularity means.",[12,78,79],{},"Modularity means splitting code into individual modules. Picture an originally one-piece object that gets broken into Lego-like blocks — each module has its own functionality and can be referenced by other modules. This makes code more readable and maintainable. The text description might feel abstract, so let's look at an example:",[81,82,87],"pre",{"className":83,"code":84,"language":85,"meta":86,"style":86},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","\u002F\u002F index.js\nconst add = (a, b) => {\n  return a + b;\n};\n\nconst subtract = (a, b) => {\n  return a - b;\n};\n\nconst multiply = (a, b) => {\n  return a * b;\n};\n\nconsole.log(add(1, 2));\nconsole.log(subtract(1, 2));\nconsole.log(multiply(1, 2));\n","js","",[88,89,90,99,135,150,156,163,187,199,204,209,233,245,250,255,284,306],"code",{"__ignoreMap":86},[91,92,95],"span",{"class":93,"line":94},"line",1,[91,96,98],{"class":97},"sGBqm","\u002F\u002F index.js\n",[91,100,102,106,110,113,117,120,123,126,129,132],{"class":93,"line":101},2,[91,103,105],{"class":104},"sOudu","const",[91,107,109],{"class":108},"scAaK"," add",[91,111,112],{"class":104}," =",[91,114,116],{"class":115},"s8XSl"," (",[91,118,38],{"class":119},"syBk-",[91,121,122],{"class":115},", ",[91,124,125],{"class":119},"b",[91,127,128],{"class":115},") ",[91,130,131],{"class":104},"=>",[91,133,134],{"class":115}," {\n",[91,136,138,141,144,147],{"class":93,"line":137},3,[91,139,140],{"class":104},"  return",[91,142,143],{"class":115}," a ",[91,145,146],{"class":104},"+",[91,148,149],{"class":115}," b;\n",[91,151,153],{"class":93,"line":152},4,[91,154,155],{"class":115},"};\n",[91,157,159],{"class":93,"line":158},5,[91,160,162],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":161},true,"\n",[91,164,166,168,171,173,175,177,179,181,183,185],{"class":93,"line":165},6,[91,167,105],{"class":104},[91,169,170],{"class":108}," subtract",[91,172,112],{"class":104},[91,174,116],{"clas